S.E.M., 0.027) and the aortic stiffness index (P=0.0029; coefficient, 0.334; 
S.E.M., 0.423) predicted longitudinal SR. Despite the presence of a successful 
repair for AoC, in the absence of hypertension, longitudinal deformation 
properties were significantly impaired. Moreover, the degree of longitudinal SR 
impairment was correlated with age at repair and aortic stiffness. Early repair 
can delay the onset of hypertension in postcoarctectomy patients, but cannot 
prevent the innate structural and functional abnormalities of the aorta and 
their deleterious effect on myocardial deformation properties.

